#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
    const int a=10;
    int *ptr;
    ptr=(int *)&a;
    *ptr=20;
    printf("%d ",a);
    printf("%d ",*ptr);
    return 0;
}

constant keyword:
If it is intialied we cannot change the value .
Constant should always intialized. 
We can change the value through pointe after typecasting it.
If it is declared as global it is stored in data sgment of intialized part.
If it is declared as local it is stored in RAM.


